1. Executive Summary
The Local County School District (LCSD) Facility Use Request and Reservation Management System is a web-based application designed to streamline the process of requesting, reviewing, and managing after-hours and weekend facility use.

Current Challenge: LCSD lacks a centralized system, resulting in miscommunication, scheduling conflicts, and administrative inefficiencies.

Solution: A user-friendly web application that routes facility use requests through a standardized approval workflow (Requestor → Principal → Operations → Calendar).

Prototype Scope: This implementation focuses on three core features from the Principal's perspective:
1.	Submit Request - Principals can submit facility use requests
2.	Review Request - Principals can review and approve/deny requests for their schools
3.	Calendar View - Principals can view and filter scheduled facility reservations

Key Constraint: This is a front-end-only prototype. Backend functionality (database, email notifications, file storage) will be simulated using JavaScript and sample data.


2. System Overview

2.1 Problem Statement
LCSD currently manages after-hours facility use through email, phone calls, and paper forms. This decentralized approach creates:
•	Communication gaps between requestors, principals, and operations staff
•	Missed HVAC scheduling resulting in energy waste and uncomfortable conditions
•	Lost contract renewals due to lack of proactive expiration tracking
•	Accountability issues when approval/denial decisions lack documentation
•	Reporting challenges for tracking custodial, maintenance, and HVAC costs

2.2 System Purpose
The system streamlines facility reservation management by:
1.	Centralizing requests in a single web-based platform
2.	Standardizing information collection through structured forms
3.	Routing requests through a defined approval workflow
4.	Maintaining a shared calendar of facility usage
5.	Generating quotes for paid facility use (conceptual in prototype)
6.	Tracking support needs (HVAC, custodial, maintenance)
7.	Retaining historical records for accountability and analysis

 
2.3 Key Stakeholders
For this prototype, the user is always a Principal with the following responsibilities:
•	Submit requests for facility use at their school
•	Review and approve/deny requests submitted by others for their school
•	View calendar of all scheduled events at their school
•	Access reference documents for facility use policies
•	Review archived requests for historical reference

Other stakeholders (conceptual, not implemented as separate roles in the prototype):
•	Public Requestors
•	LCSD Employee Requestors
•	Operations Department Staff
•	Energy Manager

2.4 System Scope
In Scope for Prototype:
•	Submit facility use requests (one-time and recurring)
•	Review pending requests with approve/deny functionality
•	View and filter calendar of scheduled events
•	Access reference documents
•	View archived requests
•	Role-based interface (Principal view only)
•	Visual status differentiation (Pending vs Approved)	

Out of Scope for Prototype:
•	Quote generation workflow (button present but disabled)
•	Report generation (button present but disabled)
•	Actual email notifications (simulated with console logs)
•	Real file uploads (filename captured, file not stored)
•	Backend database (data simulated in JavaScript)
•	User authentication/login
•	Multi-role switching
 
3. Assumptions and Constraints

3.1 Technology Stack
Required Technologies:
•	HTML5
•	CSS3 (Flexbox/Grid for layouts)
•	JavaScript (ES6+, vanilla JS)

Optional Enhancements:
•	Bootstrap or Tailwind CSS for styling
•	Font Awesome for icons
•	A lightweight calendar library (e.g., FullCalendar.js) for calendar display

Prohibited:
•	Backend frameworks (Node.js, Express, Python, etc.)
•	Database systems (PostgreSQL, MongoDB, MySQL, etc.)
•	React, Vue, Angular, or similar frameworks
•	Authentication systems
•	Actual file storage or email services

3.2 Design Constraints
Course-Imposed Constraints:
•	Front-end only: No backend server or API implementation
•	No deployment: Runs locally in browser only
•	No database: Data stored in JavaScript variables/arrays
•	Limited features: Three core features only (submit, review, calendar)
•	Single role: Principal perspective only (no role switching)

Design Goals:
1.	Accessibility: ADA-compliant, visual status differentiation using color + icons
2.	Consistency: Unified layout and navigation across all screens
3.	Simplicity: Minimal visual clutter, clear action paths
4.	Usability: All actions within 3 clicks, intuitive workflows
5.	Error Prevention: Dropdowns for constrained choices, validation before submission
6.	Responsive: Works on desktop, tablet, and mobile devices

3.3 Business Rules
Data Retention:
•	All reservation requests retained for 5 years from event date
•	Denied requests immediately archived (removed from active calendar)

Approval Workflow:
•	All requests start with status "Pending"
•	Principals can approve (→ "Approved"), deny (→ "Denied"), or request quote (→ "Quote Pending")
•	Approved events appear on calendar with visual differentiation
•	Denied events removed from calendar but retained in archived requests
Calendar Display:
•	Principals see only events for their assigned school(s)
•	Events visually differentiated by status (Pending: orange + clock icon; Approved: green + checkmark icon)

Request Types:
•	One-time: Single event on specific date
•	Recurring: Events repeating over date range (start date through end date)


4. Functional Requirements

4.1 Pre-Reservation Approval Support
•	FR-1.1: Request Submission: The system shall allow Principals to submit facility reservation requests for one-time or recurring events at their school.
•	FR-1.2: Request Notification: The system shall simulate notifying the Principal when a new request is submitted for their school (console log).
•	FR-1.3: Calendar Access: The system shall provide a calendar view showing pending and approved reservations for the Principal's school.
•	FR-1.4: Quote Generation Interface: The system shall display a "Create Quote" button on the review screen (disabled/grayed out in prototype).

4.2 Post-Decision Support
•	FR-2.1: Approval/Denial Notification: The system shall simulate notifying requestors when their request is approved or denied (console log).
•	FR-2.2: Calendar Filtering: The system shall allow filtering calendar views by month/year, school, and status.
•	FR-2.3: Denial Handling: The system shall archive denied requests and remove them from the active calendar view.
•	FR-2.4: Status Updates: The system shall update request status based on Principal decision (Pending → Approved/Denied/Quote Pending).

4.3 Ongoing Support
•	FR-3.1: Calendar Access: The system shall allow Principals to view the calendar without modification rights (view-only mode).
•	FR-3.2: Historical Record Access: The system shall provide access to archived requests for historical reference.
•	FR-3.3: Reference Document Access: The system shall provide access to facility use policy documents.
•	FR-3.4: Reporting Interface: The system shall display a "Generate Report" button on calendar view (disabled/grayed out in prototype).

 
5. Non-Functional Requirements
•	NFR-1: The system shall be web-based and accessible via modern browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge)
•	NFR-2: The system shall be responsive and function on desktop, tablet, and mobile devices
•	NFR-3: The system event calendar shall visually differentiate between pending and approved events using both color and non-color indicators (icons)
•	NFR-4: The system shall follow accessibility best practices (sufficient color contrast, keyboard navigation, semantic HTML)
•	NFR-5: The system shall maintain consistent layout and navigation across all screens
•	NFR-6: The system shall validate user input and display clear error messages for invalid data

6. Data Model

6.1 Entity Definitions
The system manages six primary entities. For the prototype, these are represented as JavaScript objects.

EVENT
Stores all facility reservation requests.
Attributes:
•	EV_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	EV_Frequency (Text): "One-time" or "Long-term"
•	EV_RequestorID (Number): USER_ID for requestor
•	EV_ReviewerID (Number): USER_ID for last user to update EV_Status
•	EV_Organization (Text): Name of organization associated with event
•	EV_OneTimeDate (Date): Date for one-time reservation
•	EV_LongTermStartDate (Date): Start date for long-term reservation
•	EV_LongTermEndDate (Date): End date for long-term reservation
•	EV_StartTime (Time): Start time for event
•	EV_EndTime (Time): End time for event
•	EV_SchoolID (Number): SCH_ID for event school
•	EV_SpaceID (Number): SPACE_ID for event space
•	EV_Attendees (Number): Expected number of attendees
•	EV_Description (Text): Description of event
•	EV_Custodial (Text): Requested custodial support
•	EV_Maintenance (Text): Requested maintenance support
•	EV_Files (File): Files uploaded by contact
•	EV_Status (Text): "Pending", "Approved", "Quote Pending", "Quote Sent", "Denied"
•	EV_Comments (Text): Comments added by Administrative Users
 
QUOTE
Stores quote details for paid facility contracts.
Attributes:
•	QUOTE_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	QUOTE_EventID (Number): EVENT_ID for associated event
•	QUOTE_CreatorID (Number): USER_ID for quote creator
•	QUOTE_Custodial (Number): Amount quoted for custodial services
•	QUOTE_Maintenance (Number): Amount quoted for maintenance services
•	QUOTE_MiscFees (Number): Amount quoted for taxes, fees, etc.
•	QUOTE_Hourly (Number): Amount quoted for hourly use of facility
•	QUOTE_Status (Text): "Pending", "Accepted", "Denied"

REFERENCE_DOCUMENT
Stores reference documents for system users.
Attributes:
•	DOC_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	DOC_Name (Text): Name of document
•	DOC_Status (Text): "Current" or "Archived"
•	DOC_UploaderID (Number): USER_ID of employee who uploaded

SCHOOL
Stores information about LCSD schools.
Attributes:
•	SCH_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	SCH_Name (Text): Name of school
•	SCH_Type (Text): "High School", "Middle School", "Elementary School", "K-12", "Special Programs"
•	SCH_StreetAddress (Text): Street number and name for school
•	SCH_City (Text): City name where school is located
•	SCH_Zip (Text): ZIP code for school
•	SCH_Status (Text): "Active" or "Inactive"
•	SCH_User (Text): USER_ID for employee users assigned to school

SPACE
Stores reservable spaces within schools.
Attributes:
•	SPACE_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	SPACE_SchoolID (Number): SCH_ID for space's school
•	SPACE_Name (Text): Description of space (e.g., "Room 200", "Gym")
•	SPACE_Capacity (Number): Maximum capacity for space
•	SPACE_Status (Text): "Available" or "Unavailable"
 
USER
Stores information about all individuals who interact with the system.
Attributes:
•	USER_ID (Number): Unique identifier
•	USER_Type (Text): "Public User", "LCSD Employee", "Principal", "Operations Department Staff", "Energy Manager"
•	USER_Name (Text): Name of user
•	USER_Email (Text): Email for user
•	USER_Phone (Text): Phone number for user
•	USER_School (Text): Schools associated with user (can be NULL for system-wide users or public users)
•	USER_Status (Text): "Active" or "Inactive"

6.2 Entity Relationships
Conceptual Relationships:
1.	User requests Event → One-to-many (via EV_RequestorID)
2.	User reviews Event → One-to-many (via EV_ReviewerID)
3.	User creates Quote → One-to-many (via QUOTE_CreatorID)
4.	Quote is generated for Event → One-to-one (via QUOTE_EventID)
5.	School contains Space → One-to-many (via SPACE_SchoolID)
6.	School hosts Event → One-to-many (via EV_SchoolID)
7.	Space holds Event → One-to-many (via EV_SpaceID)
8.	User is assigned to School → One-to-many (via USER_School)
9.	User uploads Reference Document → One-to-many (via DOC_UploaderID)

For prototype: Relationships managed through matching IDs in JavaScript objects.

