10. Data Storage & State Management

10.1 Conceptual Backend
Database Type: Relational database (PostgreSQL)
Data Organization: Data is organized into six primary tables corresponding to the entities: Event, User, School, Space, Quote, Reference Document. Tables are related through foreign keys:
•	Event references User via RequestorID and ReviewerID
•	Event references School via SchoolID
•	Event references Space via SpaceID
•	Quote references Event via EventID
•	Quote references User via CreatorID
•	Space references School via SchoolID
•	Reference Document references User via UploaderID

Data Access: System components access data through SQL operations:
•	CREATE: INSERT statements add new records (new requests, quotes, users)
•	READ: SELECT statements retrieve data for display (pending requests, calendar events, user profiles)
•	UPDATE: UPDATE statements modify existing records (status changes, comment additions)
•	ARCHIVE: Denied/completed requests flagged as archived rather than deleted

10.2 Data Lifecycle
Data Creation:
•	New Event records created when users submit reservation requests
•	New Quote records created when Operations Staff generates quotes
•	New User records created when public requestors first submit (or employees added to system)
•	New Reference Document records created when admins upload files

Data Modification:
•	Event status changes (Pending → Approved/Denied/Quote Pending/Quote Sent)
•	Event comments added during review process
•	Quote amounts adjusted by Operations Staff
•	User information updated (email changes, status changes to inactive)

Data Retrieval:
•	Pending requests queried for review lists (filtered by school association)
•	Calendar events queried for calendar display (filtered by date range, school, status)
•	User profiles queried for authentication and role-based access
•	Archived requests queried for historical reference

Data Deletion/Archival:
•	Denied requests immediately archived (removed from active calendar, retained in database)
•	All event data retained for 5 years from event date
•	After 5 years, event records automatically deleted
•	Users set to "Inactive" rather than deleted

10.2 State Management During User Sessions
Session State: When user accesses the system, temporary state is maintained for:
•	User Identity: USER_ID, USER_Type, USER_Name, USER_School
•	Current Screen: Which page user is viewing
•	Form State: Data entered in forms before submission
•	Filter State: Calendar filter selections (month, school, status)

State Persistence Rules:
Temporary State (exists only during session):
•	Form input before submission
•	Calendar filter selections
•	Selected date on calendar
•	Scroll position, UI preferences

If user leaves screen without saving:
•	Form data is lost
•	Filters reset to defaults
•	No data written to database

Persistent State (written to database):
•	Submitted reservation requests
•	Approval/denial decisions
•	Generated quotes
•	Internal comments
•	Status changes

State is persisted when user clicks:
•	"Submit" (on request form)
•	"Approve/Deny/Request Quote" (on review screen)
•	"Send Quote" (on quote generation screen)
Example - Calendar Filters: User applies filters (May 2026, Lincoln High, Approved only). These selections are stored in JavaScript variables during the session. When user navigates away from calendar or logs out, filters are cleared. Next time user (or another user) accesses calendar, default filters apply (current month, user's schools, all statuses).

10.4 Prototype Data Simulation Strategy
Since no backend database will be implemented, the AI-assisted prototype will simulate data storage using hard-coded sample data and front-end state management.
Sample Data Structure: The prototype will include predefined sample records for each data type to demonstrate system functionality:

Limitations of Prototype Simulation:
1.	No persistence across sessions: 
a.	Data changes (new requests, status updates) exist only in browser memory
b.	Refreshing page resets all data to original sample set
c.	No ability to save changes permanently
2.	No multi-user support: 
a.	All users share same sample dataset
b.	No real authentication or user sessions
c.	User role simulated with simple variable or URL parameter
3.	Email notifications simulated: 
a.	Actual emails not sent
b.	Notifications shown as console.log messages or brief UI alerts
c.	No email delivery tracking
4.	File uploads simulated: 
a.	Files not actually uploaded to server
b.	Only filename stored in event record
c.	File "download" shows alert with filename or opens sample PDF
5.	Limited data volume: 
a.	Only 5-10 sample events (vs. thousands in real system)
b.	Limited date ranges (primarily current/upcoming months)
c.	Pagination simulated but not truly necessary with small dataset
These limitations are acceptable for demonstrating system functionality and will be clearly noted in the video demonstration.

